# Cover Sheet Checklist — Massachusetts ADU

This file defines WHAT must appear on a construction plan cover sheet for a Massachusetts ADU project and WHY (per building code, statute, or professional standard). Each check includes a code basis, visual identification guidance, common deficiency patterns, and a confidence assessment.

## Scope Note

Pre-pivot, this file was California-specific (CBC, CRC, CPC, CMC, CEC, CEnC, CFC). Rewritten 2026-04-22 for Massachusetts per `PLAYBOOK.md` §23.

Applies to: any ADU permit submittal in a Massachusetts city or town, under 780 CMR (Massachusetts State Building Code, 10th Edition) and MGL Ch 40A §3 as amended by St. 2024, c. 150, §8.

## Required Elements on a Cover Sheet

### 1. Project Identification Block

**Must include:**
- Project name or type (e.g., "Accessory Dwelling Unit — 123 Elm St")
- Full property address (street, city, state, zip)
- Assessor's parcel ID (map/block/lot)
- Zoning district designation (e.g., "Residence A-2" for Cambridge; "R1" for Boston)
- Date of drawings and current revision number

**Code basis:**
- 780 CMR 107 (Construction Documents) — documents must identify project scope and location
- Municipal zoning bylaws — typically require zoning district disclosure on submitted plans

**Visual identification:** Top or bottom right of cover, block-formatted.

**Common deficiencies:**
- Address without city/zip (ambiguous for cities with multiple parcels at same street number)
- Wrong zoning district (happens when designer doesn't verify via municipal GIS)
- No parcel ID (city often requires for database cross-reference)

**Confidence:** HIGH — this is a universal requirement and easy to spot.

### 2. Project Type / Scope Statement

**Must include:**
- ADU classification: new-construction detached / attached / interior conversion / exterior conversion
- Reference to by-right status under Ch 150 of 2024 (recommended, not required)
- Scope summary (e.g., "Construct a 720 sq ft detached accessory dwelling unit with standalone electrical service")
- Any structures being demolished or altered

**Code basis:**
- MGL Ch 40A §1A definition of "accessory dwelling unit" — must be self-contained with sleeping, cooking, sanitary
- 780 CMR 107.3.1 — general project description required on documents
- 760 CMR 71.00 — documents should indicate Protected Use ADU status where applicable

**Visual identification:** Typically below project identification block.

**Common deficiencies:**
- Project scope described only as "renovation" without identifying ADU use
- Missing ADU classification — reviewer can't tell if this is new construction or conversion
- Calling it an "in-law apartment" without noting the legal-use shift under Ch 150 of 2024

**Confidence:** HIGH — ADU declaration is the crux of the submittal.

### 3. Design Professional Identification

**Must include:**
- Design professional's name
- License type and Massachusetts license number (Registered Architect, Licensed Professional Engineer, or in narrow homeowner-exempt cases, no license required)
- Professional stamp/seal (for projects requiring it)
- Signature and date

**Code basis:**
- MGL Ch 112 §60A (architects) or §81D (engineers) — licensure and use of seal
- 780 CMR 107.1 — construction documents must be prepared by a registered design professional when the project is beyond the scope of homeowner-prepared work
- Municipal requirements often reinforce this

**When IS a design professional required for an ADU?**
- **New construction, detached** — typically yes, especially structural design
- **New construction, attached** — typically yes
- **Interior conversion with structural changes** — yes if structural modifications
- **Simple interior conversion without structural work** — sometimes a homeowner can self-prepare, but most cities require licensed stamp anyway

**Exception:** Massachusetts allows a narrow "homeowner exemption" for owner-designed single-family work, but this is narrower than many homeowners think. When in doubt, stamp it.

**Visual identification:** Signed stamp in ink (for paper) or scanned stamp (for digital submittals).

**Common deficiencies:**
- Unsigned plans (stamp without signature)
- Expired license
- Out-of-state license without Massachusetts reciprocity
- Missing stamp entirely

**Confidence:** HIGH — verify stamp is applied and legible.

### 4. Governing Codes Reference Block

**Must include:**
- Massachusetts State Building Code edition: **780 CMR, 10th Edition** (as of Oct 2023)
- Adopted IRC edition: **IRC 2021** (as amended by MA)
- Adopted IBC edition: **IBC 2021** (as amended by MA, for non-residential portions if applicable)
- Massachusetts Plumbing Code: **248 CMR** (current edition)
- Massachusetts Fuel Gas Code: **248 CMR** (current edition)
- Massachusetts Electrical Code: **527 CMR 12** (adopts NEC 2023 with amendments)
- Massachusetts Energy Code applicable to the municipality:
  - Base Stretch Energy Code (most municipalities)
  - Specialized Opt-In Code (Boston, Cambridge, Somerville, Newton, Brookline, and ~55 others)
- Accessibility: **521 CMR** (Architectural Access Board) — generally NOT applicable to single-family ADUs, but cite on cover where relevant
- Fire Prevention: **527 CMR** (as applicable)
- Local zoning bylaw reference (municipal code section number for ADUs)

**Code basis:**
- 780 CMR 107.3 — documents must reference governing codes
- Professional standard — universally required on MA construction documents

**Visual identification:** Often a table or list on cover sheet, or "APPLICABLE CODES" block.

**Common deficiencies:**
- Wrong edition (still citing 780 CMR 9th Edition — that was pre-2023)
- Citing CBC, CRC, CPC, CMC (these are California codes; red flag suggesting out-of-state template)
- Missing Specialized Opt-In Code reference in municipalities that have adopted it
- Missing 527 CMR 12 for electrical
- Missing local zoning bylaw reference

**Confidence:** HIGH for code editions; MEDIUM for complete list (some reviewers are more picky than others).

