### 5. Sheet Index

**Must include:**
- Sequential list of all sheets in the set
- Sheet number, title, and latest revision date per sheet
- Sheet count total (e.g., "Sheet 3 of 18")

**Code basis:**
- 780 CMR 107.3.1 — construction documents must be coordinated and complete
- Professional standard — universally required

**Visual identification:** Table on cover sheet or separate index sheet.

**Common deficiencies:**
- Missing sheets from index (sheets referenced elsewhere but not listed)
- Sheets in set not in index
- Index not updated to latest revision

**Confidence:** HIGH — simple to cross-check against actual sheet pages.

### 6. Site Information Block (can be partial on cover, detailed on site plan sheet)

**Must include:**
- Lot area (sq ft)
- Zoning district
- Setback requirements applicable (front, side, rear, accessory)
- Height limit applicable
- Existing vs. proposed lot coverage
- Existing vs. proposed FAR (if applicable)

**Code basis:**
- Municipal zoning bylaw — dimensional requirements
- MGL Ch 40A §3 — dimensional regulation reserved to localities
- 780 CMR 107.3.1 — document must show compliance with applicable codes

**Visual identification:** Usually a zoning compliance table.

**Common deficiencies:**
- No zoning compliance table at all
- Table shows only proposed, not existing (reviewer can't verify compliance of addition)
- Height calculated incorrectly (especially on sloped lots)
- FAR calculation excludes floor area that municipal bylaw includes (basements, garages, attics with certain headroom)

**Confidence:** HIGH for presence of table; MEDIUM for correctness of FAR calculation.

### 7. Vicinity / Location Map

**Must include:**
- Small-scale map showing project location
- North arrow
- Nearby streets for reference
- Optional: parcel outline

**Code basis:**
- 780 CMR 107.3.1 — documents identify location
- Standard permitting requirement — most MA cities require vicinity map

**Visual identification:** Small inset map, typically top-right of cover.

**Common deficiencies:**
- Missing entirely
- Wrong scale (too zoomed in or zoomed out to be useful)
- No north arrow

**Confidence:** HIGH — present/absent and map-like.

### 8. Owner Information

**Must include:**
- Property owner name
- Owner contact information (address, phone, email)
- Sign-off from owner if applicant is a contractor/designer

**Code basis:**
- 780 CMR 105.1.1 — applicant authorization
- Municipal permit applications — owner authorization standard

**Visual identification:** Block with owner info; signature line.

**Common deficiencies:**
- Missing owner signature authorizing contractor/designer to apply
- Owner name differs from assessor records (may flag ownership question)

**Confidence:** HIGH.

### 9. Assumed Building Code Classification

**Must include:**
- Use group classification (R-3 for single-family / typical residential ADU)
- Construction type (V-B most common for wood-frame residential)
- Occupancy load if relevant

**Code basis:**
- 780 CMR / IRC Ch 3 — classification of dwellings
- 780 CMR / IBC Ch 3 for any non-residential portion

**Note on ADUs:** An ADU is typically classified R-3 (residential one- or two-family dwellings) under IRC 2021. For projects stacking multiple ADUs or in multi-family structures, use group may shift to R-2.

**Visual identification:** Code compliance block.

**Common deficiencies:**
- Wrong use group (e.g., classifying as R-2 when R-3 applies)
- Missing construction type

**Confidence:** MEDIUM — requires knowledge of code classification.

## ADU-Specific Checks (Post-Ch 150)

Post-Ch 150 of 2024, cover sheets should also include (recommended, not universally required):

- **By-right declaration:** "This accessory dwelling unit is submitted under MGL Ch 40A §3 as amended by St. 2024, c. 150, §8 (Protected Use ADU per 760 CMR 71.00)." Indicates the submittal should receive administrative (non-discretionary) review.
- **Dimensional compliance:** ADU gross floor area compared to primary dwelling — showing compliance with the "≤900 sq ft or ≤50% of primary" rule
- **Parking compliance:** Notation of parking provision (0 or 1 spaces) with basis (transit proximity if applicable)
- **Energy code status:** Which energy code applies (Stretch vs. Specialized)

## Common Cross-Reference Items

The cover typically references content on other sheets:
- Site plan with setback, coverage, FAR
- Floor plans
- Elevations
- Structural drawings if applicable
- Mechanical, plumbing, electrical (M/P/E)
- Energy code compliance documentation

Cross-reference integrity is a reviewer's first-pass check — does the cover's sheet index match the actual sheets, and do items listed as "see sheet X" actually appear on sheet X?

## Cover Sheet — Quick-Review Decision Tree

```
Can you identify the project from the cover alone? (address + ADU type + scope)
├── NO → Deficient. Request revised cover.
└── YES → Continue.

Is a Massachusetts-licensed design professional stamped and signed?
├── NO → If required for this project scope, deficient. If homeowner-prepared (rare, narrow exception), verify exemption.
└── YES → Continue.

Are governing codes listed and current (780 CMR 10th Edition, IRC 2021, etc.)?
├── NO → Deficient. Flag which codes are missing or outdated.
└── YES → Continue.

Is zoning compliance demonstrated (district, setbacks, height, coverage/FAR)?
├── NO → Deficient. Request zoning compliance table.
└── YES → Continue.

Does the sheet index match the sheets in the set?
├── NO → Deficient. Flag mismatch.
└── YES → Cover passes. Continue to next sheet.
```

## Reviewer Confidence Notes

When PermitMonkey reviews a cover sheet, the confidence calibration is:

- **HIGH confidence items:** Project ID, stamp/signature, sheet index, code edition
- **MEDIUM confidence items:** Use group classification, FAR calculation, ADU-specific post-Ch 150 declarations (still evolving in practice)
- **LOW confidence items:** Designer stamp authenticity (image-only check), detailed zoning bylaw citations per municipality (requires ma-city-research skill)

## When to Escalate to Human Review

Flag for human attention if:
- Designer stamp is illegible or apparently modified
- Governing codes cited are for another jurisdiction (CA: CBC, CRC, CPC; NY: NYC Building Code; etc.)
- Project type is ambiguous (e.g., cover says "renovation" but floor plans show a new detached structure)
- Owner differs materially from assessor records

